Building DKMS drivers using Distrobox

The gist of the tutorial is the following: To build a module using DKMS on a Distrobox container, we need to copy the kernel headers from the host to the container, install DKMS on the container, obtain the driver we want to build, and then add the built modules to the hostâ€™s root directory.

So, first, we need to install DKMS on a container; letâ€™s assume we use a container similar to the tutorial to use Distrobox. Again, we will use the option â€“no-install-recommends to avoid installing a kernel package in the container; this way, we avoid future problems when building the modules.

cp -r /usr/src/linux-headers-$(uname -r) $(pwd)

Then, we copy the resulting directory to /usr/src in the containersâ€™ root.

distrobox-enter --name debian12-distrobox -- sudo cp -r linux-headers-$(uname -r) /usr/src/

Before building the modules, we need to create the directory structure in /lib. To do this, run the following command.

distrobox-enter --name debian12-distrobox -- sudo ln -svf /usr/src/linux-headers-$(uname -r) /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build

Loading the built DKMS modules on Nitrux

Now, on a separate tab outside of the container, we can copy the files to the root directory of Nitrux and tell DKMS to auto-install them.

  • âš ï¸ Important: The commands below create, copy, edit, or move files in the root directory; see XFS Features and Root Immutability in Nitrux.
sudo cp -r *.ko /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/updates/dkms/
sudo dkms autoinstall -k $(uname -r)
sudo cp -r *.ko /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/updates/dkms/ sudo dkms autoinstall -k $(uname -r)
sudo cp -r *.ko /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/updates/dkms/
sudo dkms autoinstall -k $(uname -r)

Then, we build the list of module dependencies with depmod again and load the modules with modprobe to use them immediately.

sudo depmod
sudo modprobe -a ashmem_linux binder_linux
sudo depmod sudo modprobe -a ashmem_linux binder_linux
sudo depmod 
sudo modprobe -a ashmem_linux binder_linux

Or, we can add a configuration file to load the modules during boot. The file should be in the path /etc/modules-load.d and can have any name.

>> anbox-modules.conf printf "%s\n" \
'# Load Anbox ashmem and binder modules' \
'' \
'ashmem_linux' \
'binder_linux' \
''
sudo mv anbox-modules.conf /etc/modules-load.d/
>> anbox-modules.conf printf "%s\n" \ '# Load Anbox ashmem and binder modules' \ '' \ 'ashmem_linux' \ 'binder_linux' \ '' sudo mv anbox-modules.conf /etc/modules-load.d/
>> anbox-modules.conf printf "%s\n" \
    '# Load Anbox ashmem and binder modules' \
    '' \
    'ashmem_linux' \
    'binder_linux' \
    ''

sudo mv anbox-modules.conf /etc/modules-load.d/

Now, the modules will be loaded when the distribution boots.
